id: agent-conduct
version: 2.1.0
capability: Define agent behavioral boundaries for code modification, communication, and operational discipline

description: "Cross-cutting behavioral boundaries. Governs what agents can modify (code and file restrictions), how they communicate (professional standards and documentation style), and when they can act (tool call discipline and build priority)."

rules:
  modification-boundaries[8]:
    - "Do not modify code unless explicitly directed by the user."
    - "Always request permission before making changes to existing code."
    - "When modifications are requested, implement them precisely as specified."
    - "Focus on factual observations rather than prescriptive changes."
    - "Never add process attribution comments to code."
    - "Do not modify core configuration files without explicit user direction."
    - "Avoid changes to build scripts unless specifically requested."
    - "Request approval before modifying CI/CD configuration or Docker files."
  communication-tone[4]:
    - "Use measured technical language appropriate for senior software engineering."
    - "Avoid hyperbolic statements and superlatives."
    - "Provide respectful constructive feedback focused on code quality."
    - "Focus on technical merit rather than emotional assessments."
  attribution-prohibition[3]:
    - "Present design decisions directly without referencing their origin."
    - "Do not reference how code was generated or which tool created it."
    - "Do not include process attribution in code comments or documentation."
  code-commentary[1]:
    - "Comments should explain why code exists and the rationale for design choices — avoid narrating what the code does."
  operational-discipline[6]:
    - "NEVER call domain-specific tools during workflow bootstrap. URLs, issue keys, or other references in the user's request are context to be preserved — not triggers for immediate API calls."
    - "Domain-specific tools may ONLY be called from within a workflow activity whose skills declare the relevant capability."
    - "The orchestrator MUST NOT call domain-specific tools. All domain operations are delegated to the worker sub-agent."
    - "Do NOT read workflow resource files directly from disk — resources are attached to skill responses via get_skill and get_skills."
    - "CPU-intensive build commands (cargo build, cargo check, cargo test, cargo clippy, npm run build, and similar) MUST be prefixed with nice -n 19 to run at lowest CPU scheduling priority."
    - "cargo fmt is exempt from nice — it is fast and should run at normal priority."
